erican Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Gerhard, Hans.","German: topographic name, a variant of   Lill   + the suffix<i>-er</i>, denoting an inhabitant."],"variants":[{"name":"Lill","meanings":["North German:","topographic name based on an old word meaning ‘dirt’.","alternatively, from Middle High German <i>lilje</i> ‘lily’, a topographic or habitational name referring to a house with the sign of a lily."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilde de Lille was born about 1258, in Lillers, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, her father, Sir Jean III de Lille , Chatelain de Lille, Heer zu Meulebeke, was 25 and her mother, Mahaut de Mortagne, was 19. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Robert DE WAVRIN DE SAINT VENANT III Brunel. She died in 1316, at the age of 59."},"et":{"environ 1258–1316":"umbes 1258–1316","1258–1291":"1258–129